Trochaic Septenarii, long verses which would often occupy two lines instead of one in A, the exact number of lines supposed to be missing cannot be stated. It may have been as many as 40.

914. Carni. This spelling is required by the metre. The Abl. Sg. of the Third Declension had two forms of case-suffix, (1) -ἑ <from an original -ῑ, properly the Locative-suffix, like the Gk. -ῖ of the Dative), (2) -ῖ (from an original ad). Of Consonant-stems with -ῐ in Abl. Sg. we have in Plautus, eg. parieti Cas. 140 (MSS. -e), pumici Pers. 41 (MSS. -e) (cf. obieci Pers. 203).

915. Praetruneauit. Cf. v. 902. The apparent reading of the Palimpsest praermzcauit may bc right, from runcare, ‘to wecd'

917. Seriae, “jars for preserves, much too large for ordinary cooking purposes; but Ergasilus is represented as dissatisfied with all ordinary provisions for eating.” Morris.

918. Reeclusit. Sec note on v. 923. We should spell with double c, if for nothing else, to guard against the mistako of supposing that a mute and liquid could constitute length by ‘position' in Plautus (see Introd. ii. ξ 30).
